<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Adversary fixture: rdf:parseType="Literal"

  RDF/XML spec §2.9 (rdf:parseType="Literal"):
  When a property element carries rdf:parseType="Literal", its content
  is NOT further parsed as RDF/XML. Instead, the raw XML infoset
  (serialised back to a canonical XML string) is used as the *string
  value* of an rdf:XMLLiteral typed literal. The datatype IRI is:

    http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#XMLLiteral

  This fixture uses nested markup in the Literal content, including
  an element from a different namespace. The critical edge cases are:

    1. The nested XML is *not* interpreted as more RDF triples.
    2. The resulting object is an rdf:XMLLiteral, not a plain string.
    3. Namespace declarations on the property element are included in
       the serialised infoset per the XML Literal spec (RDF/XML §3.2).

  Divergence hypothesis: parsers that do not implement parseType="Literal"
  will either reject the document or treat the content as nested node
  elements, emitting incorrect triples. Parsers that strip namespace
  declarations from the serialised infoset will produce a literal value
  that differs from the canonical form expected by the XPath data model.

  Spec-ref: https://www.w3.org/TR/rdf-syntax-grammar/#section-Syntax-parsetype-Literal
  Production: parseTypeLiteralPropertyElt
-->
<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
         xmlns:ex="http://example.org/vocab#">
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/doc/42">
    <ex:markup rdf:parseType="Literal">
      <b xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">bold text</b>
    </ex:markup>
  </rdf:Description>
</rdf:RDF>
